content: If you enjoyed game dev story, this game is just as good. If you are struggling matching themes there are good guides on on the wiki page.

Absolutely disappointed. :/ The idea is great, the execution bad. Plot arc combinations aren't explained at all. No option to decide if to start oneshot or series without ordered by publisher. No option to drop a project. No option to doodle on a oneshot while writing a series. Started over five times, got to year two, but the bad mechanics keep me from wanting to play any more. If I hadn't spent money on the game I'd have uninstalled it a lot sooner.
could use more paths, and choices, such as becoming a publish company ourselves.

Definately a much more simplified Kairosoft game this time. Theres not a lot of interesting mechanics here and once you get to a good point publishing series it just seems very repetitive. Other Kairosoft games have done a much better job at keeping this repetitive loop going and this game just dosen't do it as well. On the other hand I do love manga so that definately helped in keeping me interested for a bit.

Another gem from Kairosoft, sticking to the classic strategy / management formula which serves them so well. Often imitated but never bettered, when Kairosoft aren't dipping their toes into free to play territory, they remain comfortably seated in the charming/intense/pixel art/simulation throne on Android. Even their titles you think you're not interested in - horse racing, or running a sushi bar - are second to none.

The biggest issue I have is that the game largely seems to play itself a lot of the time.  Once you get serialized, the core gameplay loop is to wait for it to end by repeating the same tasks. It's feels like the Sims if your Mangaka is stuck in the house.  Maybe it's commentary. Still it is a bit different, though still decidedly a Kairosoft game and has its charm.
Finally, a return to the old formula of Kairosoft games.  A fresh change from some of the recent disappointments.
